Use 2 files for this practical, because external CSS needs a separate file.
1) HTML file (index.html)
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>CSS Example</title>

    <!-- Internal CSS -->
    <style>
        h2 {
            color: blue;
        }

        table {
            border-collapse: collapse;
        }

        th, td {
            border: 1px solid black;
            padding: 8px;
        }
    </style>

    <!-- External CSS -->
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>

    <!-- Inline CSS -->
    <h1 style="color:red;">Student Details</h1>

    <h2>Using Internal, External and Inline CSS</h2>

    <table>
        <tr>
            <th>Name</th>
            <th>City</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Arafat</td>
            <td>Sangli</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Rahul</td>
            <td>Pune</td>
        </tr>
    </table>

</body>
</html>


2) External CSS file (style.css)

body {
    background-color: lightgray;
    font-family: Arial;
}


 
Code explanation
External CSS
body {
    background-color: lightgray;
    font-family: Arial;
}
This is written in a separate file.
It changes the page background and font.
Internal CSS
<style>
CSS written inside the HTML file, inside the <head> section.
It styles:
•	h2 heading color 
•	table borders 
•	padding inside table cells 
Inline CSS
<h1 style="color:red;">
CSS written directly inside an HTML tag.
________________________________________
Short viva explanation
If teacher says “Explain your program,” you can say:
“This web page uses all three types of CSS. Inline CSS styles the first heading, internal CSS styles the second heading and table, and external CSS changes the page background and font.”
